      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_5",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(a) ( ) Let L be any regular language. Then the number of equivalence classes respect to language L (i.e. x ~L y, if for all z € L*, xz E L iff yz E L) is finite.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1622176696497189,
          0.44186046525362854,
          0.876796721644325,
          0.47529069735538304
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_6",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(b) ( ) The language {a\"\"w/wE {a, b}* *, nE N, and |w| = 2n} is context-free.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1601642846063008,
          0.48401162747943,
          0.8583162178167605,
          0.5000000002494945
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_7",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(c) ( ) The language {\"M\" \"w\" |M accepts w in less than 2016 steps } is not recursive.",
        "bbox": [
          0.16016427894561908,
          0.5071924598620758,
          0.874743300725839,
          0.539349388930071
        ],
        "order": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_8",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(d) ( ) The language {\"M\" | M is a TM and L(M) is Context-free but L(M) is not regular, is not recursive.",
        "bbox": [
          0.15811088203063114,
          0.5493551586268136,
          0.8747433130823054,
          0.5828488372351387
        ],
        "order": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_9",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(e) ( ) The language {\"M\" \"M,\" | M, and Me are TMs, and M, halts on e but Ma doesn't halt on e} is recursively enumerable, but not recursive.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1601642917279597,
          0.5915178572250318,
          0.8747433135081795,
          0.6264880952639315
        ],
        "order": 11
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_11",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(g) ( ) Let A and B be two disjoint recursively enumerable languages. If AU B is also be recursively enumerable, then it is possible that neither A nor B is decidable.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1601642831661461,
          0.674355158269708,
          0.8747971117257376,
          0.727133996785131
        ],
        "order": 13
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocai_jiaocai_en_310_12",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(h) ( ) Let H10 = {\"M\" |M is a TM and 10 € L(M)} and 1 and 2 are recursive functions. If H10 Sm L and H1o Sm L, then L is recursive enumerable but not recursive.",
        "bbox": [
          0.16016429388401707,
          0.7353670636440793,
          0.8747433206689664,
          0.7848837207188762
        ],
        "order": 14
